        // ── AI Help & Smart Search (Article) ─────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "AI Help & Smart Search",
            Slug = "ai-help-and-search",
            Summary = "The two AI features in the top header on every page: the AI Help panel (a chat that remembers your conversation and suggests related training) and the AI column in search (plain-language answers and matches you can jump to).",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/dashboard"]""",
            Tags = """["ai","help","search","header","rag"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## AI Help & Smart Search\n\nBesides the AI page, two more AI features live in the top header and follow you on every page. They're separate from the AI page assistants and work a little differently — this module covers both.\n\n### 1. The AI Help Panel\n\nClick the **robot icon** in the header to open the AI Help panel — a chat that slides out on the right. This is your in-app help: ask it how to do something in Forge and it answers in plain language. The icon only shows when AI is available for your setup.\n\n**Welcome screen and starters.** When the panel is empty it shows a welcome message and four starter buttons — 'How do I create a new job?', 'How does the quote to order workflow work?', 'How do I track inventory?', and 'What keyboard shortcuts are available?'. Click one to send it, or type your own question at the bottom and press Enter.\n\n**Answers appear as you go.** Replies come in a bit at a time, so you see the answer build in real time. They can include headings, lists, bold text, and code.\n\n**Related training links.** After an answer, the panel may show a 'Related training:' section with up to three links, picked to match the page you're on. Click one to open that training module.\n\n**Your chat sticks around.** Unlike the AI page (which forgets your chat when you leave), the AI Help panel remembers your conversation in your browser. It survives a refresh, closing the tab, and reopening later — and it stays in sync across your open Forge tabs. It keeps your most recent 50 messages.\n\n**Clearing.** Click the **restart** icon in the panel header to start fresh, which clears the saved chat. Click the **X**, click outside the panel, or click the robot icon again to just hide it without clearing anything.\n\n### 2. The AI Column in Global Search\n\nThe header search box (press **Ctrl+K** to jump to it) is a normal search — type and it finds jobs, parts, customers, and other records by keyword. When AI is available, the results split into **two columns**:\n\n- **Left column — Results:** the usual keyword matches. Click one to open that record.\n- **Right column — AI Results:** an AI view of the same search. While it's working you'll see a spinner and a 'Thinking…' label.\n\n**The AI answer.** At the top of the AI column, you may get a short written **answer** — a direct, plain-language response drawn from your own data.\n\n**AI matches.** Below the answer is a list of matches found by meaning, not just exact words. Each shows the matching text, what kind of record it is, and how strong the match is. Click any one to **jump straight to that record** — so the AI column also helps you find records a plain keyword search might miss.\n\n### When to Use Which\n\n- **Use the AI Help panel** for 'how do I…' or 'what does this do' questions about Forge itself — steps, workflow, where to click, keyboard shortcuts.\n- **Use AI search** when you're after a specific record but only remember a description or detail, not the exact number — it matches by meaning and lets you jump right to the record.\n\n### Availability\n\nBoth depend on AI being turned on and available for your setup. If AI is off or unavailable, the robot icon disappears from the header and search shows only the usual Results column — everything else in Forge works exactly as before.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── AI Drafting & Summarizing (QuickRef) ─────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "AI Drafting & Summarizing",
            Slug = "ai-drafting-summarizing",
            Summary = "Reference for the AI generate (drafting) and summarize affordances: what they do, where they appear, what they send, and how they behave when AI is unavailable.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.QuickRef,
            EstimatedMinutes = 3,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/ai"]""",
            Tags = """["ai","drafting","summarize","reference"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"title":"AI Drafting & Summarizing","groups":[{"heading":"What These Do","items":[{"label":"Drafting","value":"Writes new text from an instruction you give it — for example a job description, a customer email, a part description, or documentation. You tell it what you want; it hands back text you can edit and use."},{"label":"Summarizing","value":"Boils a block of existing text down to a short summary — for example turning a long note, description, or thread into its key points."},{"label":"How it differs from chat","value":"Drafting and summarizing are one-and-done — you ask once and get one result. There's no back-and-forth and no memory of earlier requests, unlike the AI Help panel or an AI page assistant."}]},{"heading":"How They Behave","items":[{"label":"One request, one result","value":"Each draft or summary is a single request that returns one block of text all at once. There are no follow-up turns."},{"label":"You can edit the result","value":"The result is a starting point, never final. Read it over and edit it before you save it onto a record. The AI never changes your data on its own."},{"label":"What it works from","value":"Drafting works from the instruction you give. Summarizing works from the text you hand it. Neither goes searching through your records — it only uses what you provide."}]},{"heading":"Availability & Limits","items":[{"label":"Only when AI is on","value":"Both need AI turned on and available for your setup. When AI is off or unavailable, drafting and summarizing are hidden or greyed out — the screen still works fine without them."},{"label":"Fails gracefully","value":"If a draft or summary doesn't come through, nothing breaks: you keep what you had, and no half-finished text is written to a record."},{"label":"Stays in-house","value":"Drafting and summarizing run on the same AI as the rest of Forge's AI features. Your data stays within your setup — nothing is sent to an outside AI provider."}]},{"heading":"Good Use Cases","items":[{"label":"First-draft writing","value":"Job descriptions, customer emails, part or process descriptions, internal documentation — anywhere the blank page is the hard part."},{"label":"Condensing","value":"Turning a long note, inspection comment, or description into a one- or two-line summary for a header or report."},{"label":"Not a system of record","value":"Don't treat AI output as official data. It's a writing aid — a person reviews it and owns the final text."}]}]}"""
        });

        // ── Configuring AI Assistants (Walkthrough) ──────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Configuring AI Assistants (Admin)",
            Slug = "ai-configuring-assistants",
            Summary = "Admin walkthrough of the AI Assistants panel: create, edit, and delete assistants; set an assistant's instructions; limit which records it can use; manage starter questions, active state, and order.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Walkthrough,
            EstimatedMinutes = 7,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/ai-assistants"]""",
            Tags = """["ai","admin","assistant","configuration","walkthrough"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/admin/ai-assistants","startButtonLabel":"Tour AI Assistant Setup","steps":[{"element":".panel-header","popover":{"title":"AI Assistants Panel","description":"This is where admins set up AI assistants, under Admin → AI Assistants. The header shows how many exist. Every active assistant here appears on the AI page for users. Only admins see this tab.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".action-btn--create","popover":{"title":"New Assistant","description":"Click 'New Assistant' to open the editor. The same editor opens when you click an existing row to change it. We'll walk through the fields next.","side":"left"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"The Assistants List","description":"Each row shows the assistant's icon, name, category, how many data filters are set ('All' when none), and whether it's active. Click a row to edit it. Built-in assistants can be edited but not deleted; ones you create can be deleted.","side":"top"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Name, Category, Description, and Look","description":"Open the assistant editor to set how it appears to users. Name and Category are required. Category can be General, HR, Procurement, Sales, or Custom. The description shows on the assistant's card and welcome screen. Pick an icon and color to give it a clear look; a live preview shows the result.","side":"top"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Instructions — how the assistant behaves","description":"Open the assistant editor to set its instructions. This shapes how it answers — its style, tone, and focus. It's where you tell an HR assistant to answer like an HR specialist, or a purchasing assistant to focus on sourcing. Users never see these instructions; they work quietly behind every answer.","side":"top"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Which records it can use","description":"Open the assistant editor to set which of your records the assistant may pull from when answering. Leave it empty to allow all records; or pick specific kinds — jobs, parts, customers, vendors, and more — to keep, say, an HR assistant limited to employee data. This keeps each assistant focused and out of areas it shouldn't touch.","side":"top"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Starter Questions","description":"Open the assistant editor to set the suggested questions on its welcome screen. Type a question, click Add, and it joins the list; remove any with the X. These are the clickable prompts users see before they type anything — give each assistant a few good ones for its area.","side":"top"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Active, Order, and Advanced","description":"Open the assistant editor to set whether it's active — turn this off to retire an assistant without deleting it. Order sets its place in the sidebar list. Under Advanced Settings you can fine-tune how creative its answers are and how much data it draws on — leave the defaults unless you have a reason to change them. Save, and it shows up for users right away.","side":"top"}}]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "AI Assistant — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "ai-reference",
            Summary = "Power-user and admin details for the AI Assistant: fine-tuning an assistant's answers, built-in vs. custom assistants and deleting, what happens when AI is off or unavailable, how AI search finds your records, and how the Help panel syncs and caps its history.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/ai"]""",
            Tags = """["ai","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Fine-tuning an assistant's answers\n\nEach assistant has two advanced settings, found under **Advanced Settings** in the assistant editor (Admin → AI Assistants).\n\n- **Answer creativity** (default **0.7**, range 0–1) — how varied the answers are. Lower (toward 0) makes them more predictable and conservative; higher (toward 1) makes them more varied. Leave it at the default unless an assistant needs tighter, more repeatable answers.\n- **How much data it draws on** (default **5**, range 1–20) — how many pieces of your data the assistant pulls in when answering. More gives it more to work from but makes answers slower; fewer is faster but narrower. Five is a balanced starting point.\n\nBoth are set per assistant, not for all of them at once — a focused HR assistant and a broad general assistant can be tuned separately.\n\n## Built-in vs. custom assistants, and deleting\n\nAssistants are either **built-in** (they come with Forge and show a 'Built In' label) or **custom** (created by an admin).\n\n- **Built-in assistants can be edited but not deleted.** To retire one, turn off its **Active** switch — it disappears from the AI page for users but stays set up.\n- **Custom assistants can be deleted.** As everywhere in Forge, a delete just hides the assistant rather than wiping it out.\n- The **General** category is special: the AI page's general option points to whichever assistant is set to General. Keep one General assistant active so that option always lands somewhere.\n\n## When AI is off or unavailable\n\nAll AI features share one on/off setting for your install.\n\n- **AI turned off:** the header robot icon is hidden, the AI search column doesn't appear, and the AI page, drafting, and summarizing are unavailable. The rest of Forge is unaffected.\n- **AI on but unavailable:** the AI runs in-house, within your own setup. If it's temporarily down, AI features step aside instead of breaking the page — search falls back to plain keyword results, and chat, drafting, and summarizing quietly do nothing rather than saving half-finished text. Nothing is ever sent to an outside AI provider.\n\n## How AI search finds your records\n\nThe assistants' grounding and the AI search column work off a prepared index of your data, not a live scan.\n\n- Your records are broken into pieces and prepared so the AI can match them by meaning, not just exact words.\n- Forge refreshes this index automatically on a schedule (roughly every half hour), so newly created or edited records become findable without any manual step.\n- Each assistant's **allowed records** setting limits which kinds of records it may draw on — that's how you keep, say, an HR assistant grounded only in employee data. Leave it empty and it can use all record types.\n\n## The AI Help panel: syncing and its message limit\n\nThe header AI Help panel remembers your chat differently from the AI page (which forgets it when you leave).\n\n- **Saved in your browser, per user.** Your chat is saved locally, so it survives a refresh, closing the tab, and reopening later.\n- **In sync across tabs.** Send a message in one tab and the conversation updates in your other open Forge tabs — it's one shared conversation.\n- **Keeps the last 50 messages.** Only your most recent 50 messages are kept; older ones roll off.\n- **Clearing** wipes the saved chat (the restart icon). If your browser's storage is full, that turn just may not be saved — the conversation still works while you're in it.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded AI Assistant training modules");
    }
}
